Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

By Sarah Pedigo¶

Note: This dataset is from Prosper loan company who specializes in personal loans. A personal loan is a loan for anything that is not a house, car, or college payment. They can be used for weddings, paying off credit card debt, repairing your house, funding a trip, and many other things. Introduction will continue after preliminary wrangling.

Introduction¶

This is a very large dataset. Structurally, it has over 100,000 entries and 81 columns. The columns include things like APR, borrower's monthly income, and term of loan. The first main feature that I will explore is the relationship Prosper score has with the other selected variables. The second main feature that I will explore is the effect income has on different variables. The features of this dataset that will help me in assessing the main feature include revolving credit balance, debt to income ratio, and reported monthly income. These things are all factored into credit scores, so they give me insight as to what the credit grade and Prosper score were based on.

Variable definitions¶

  1. CreditGrade- The Credit rating that was assigned at the time the listing went live. Applicable for listings pre-2009 period and will only be populated for those listings.
  2. BorrowerAPR- The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  3. ProsperRating- (numeric) The Prosper Rating assigned at the time the listing was created: 0 - N/A, 1 - HR, 2 - E, 3 - D, 4 - C, 5 - B, 6 - A, 7 - AA. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  4. ProsperScore- A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  5. IsBorrowerHomeowner- A Borrower will be classified as a homeowner if they have a mortgage on their credit profile or provide documentation confirming they are a homeowner.
  6. RevolvingCreditBalance- Dollars of revolving credit at the time the credit profile was pulled.
  7. DebtToIncomeRatio- The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled. This value is Null if the debt to income ratio is not available. This value is capped at 10.01. (any debt to income ratio larger than 1000% will be returned as 1001%).
  8. StatedMonthlyIncome- The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  9. ProsperPrincipalBorrowed- Total principal borrowed on Prosper loans at the time the listing was created. This value will be null if the borrower had no prior loans.
  10. MonthlyLoanPayment- The scheduled monthly loan payment.

Summary of findings¶

There is almost equal distribution between homeowners and non-homeowners. 4 is the most common Prosper score among the whole group. The majority of scores seem to be between 4 and 8. The majority of credit grades are between B and D. The majority of loans are current. A high Prosper score can predict a high monthly payment due to higher credit limits. Prosper score tends to go up with income. There is no suggested relationship between being a homeowner and Prosper score. Revolving credit balance tends to go up with Prosper score. A lower Prosper score can predict a high APR. Principal borrowed and monthly loan payment are two variables where we see a notable difference between the upper and lower income groups. The only significant correlation present is between Prosper rating and Prosper score. There is a slight correlation between monthly income and Prosper rating/Prosper score There is a slight negative correlation between debt to income ratio and all other variables explored in the scatter matrix.
